S5.T1.caption: TABLE I:  Comparision of dance generation on the AIST++ dataset. For simplicity,  ↑ ↑ \uparrow  means higher is better,  ↓ ↓ \downarrow  means lower is better and  → → \rightarrow  means closer to the ground truth is better. During inference, akin to EDGE  [ 6 ] , the guidance weight  w 𝑤 w  is set to 2 by default, and the results obtained with  w = 1 𝑤 1 w=1  are also reported to explore the influence of amplified conditions.
references:
We choose EDGE [6] as our baseline. For different approaches, we generate 20 pieces of dances with 5-second length, covering 10 different genres of AIST++. Quantitative results are summarized in Table I.
Our method performs favorably against EDGE [6] on most metrics. Specifically, there is a significant improvement in the Beat Alignment Score metric, which is main metric of dance generation, suggesting that the dances generated of our method are more in tune with the musical melody. Moreover, our method achieves the lowest F​I​Dk𝐹𝐼subscript𝐷𝑘FID_{k}, which is defined on motion velocities and energies, reflecting the physical characteristics of dance. The superiority of F​I​Dk𝐹𝐼subscript𝐷𝑘FID_{k} demonstrates that the proposed DGSDP can generated more realistic dance movements. In addition, our method achieves the closest approximation to the ground-truth values of D​i​vk𝐷𝑖subscript𝑣𝑘Div_{k} and D​i​vg𝐷𝑖subscript𝑣𝑔Div_{g}, revealing the capability to generate more diverse dance movements of our method rather than converging to a few fixed future motions.

references: While comparing our method with \scriptsize{1}⃝ and \scriptsize{2}⃝ in Table IV, we observe that the Beat Alignment Score and D​i​vk𝐷𝑖subscript𝑣𝑘Div_{k} achieve the optimal performance when Jukebox is utilized as the feature extractor; PFC attains its peak performance with Encodec serving as the feature extractor; and F​I​Dk𝐹𝐼subscript𝐷𝑘FID_{k}, F​I​Dg𝐹𝐼subscript𝐷𝑔FID_{g} and D​i​vg𝐷𝑖subscript𝑣𝑔Div_{g} exhibit the best results when Librosa is employed as the feature extractor.

Style Description Prompts: Previous related work [17] has attempted to use genres as additional conditions for music generation for dance. We do ablation experiments on the input of the Style Modulation module, using genres instead of style description prompts. As shown in \scriptsize{3}⃝circled-\scriptsize{3}\normalsize{\scriptsize{3}⃝} in Table IV, performance degrades significantly on Beat Alignment Score and PFC when genres are used as input to Style Modulation. The possible reason for this is that genres contain less information than style description prompts.

Style Modulation:  To verify the effectiveness of the Style Modulation module, we remove the Style Modulation module and replace it with concatenating music conditions c𝑐c and style description prompts s𝑠s simply, which then enters the MCSAD block together. The results are illustrated in \scriptsize{4}⃝ in Table IV. We can find that simply concatenating music conditions and style description prompts performs worse on most metrics than including the Style Modulation module.

Next, in order to investigate the importance of the combination of Style Modulation and Style Description Prompts in DGSDP, we remove the Style Modulation module and we don’t use any prompts either. So, the model only has music conditions. The results are shown in \scriptsize{5}⃝ in Table IV. We can see that the performances are obviously worse without any text prompts. From this we can conclude that it is quite important for Style Modulation and Style Description Prompts to work together.
